+## Class: AsyncLocal
+<!-- YAML
+added: REPLACEME
+-->
+
+This class is used to create asynchronous state between callbacks and promise
+chains. It allows you to keep variables throughout the lifetime of a web request
+or any other asynchronous duration. It is similar to thread local storage
+ in other languages.
+
+The following example builds a logger that will always know the current HTTP
+request and use it to display enhanced logs without needing to explicitly pass
+the current HTTP request to it.
+
+```js
+const { AsyncLocal } = require('async_hooks');
+const http = require('http');
+
+const kReq = 'CURRENT_REQUEST';
+const asyncLocal = new AsyncLocal();
+
+function log(...args) {
+  const store = asyncLocal.getStore();
+  // Make sure the store exists and it contains a request.
+  if (store && store.has(kReq)) {
+    const req = store.get(kReq);
+    // Prints `GET /items ERR could not do something
+    console.log(req.method, req.url, ...args);
+  } else {
+    console.log(...args);
+  }
+}
+
+http.createServer((request, response) => {
+  asyncLocal.run(() => {
+    const store = asyncLocal.getStore();
+    store.set(kReq, request);
+    someAsyncOperation((err, result) => {
+      if (err) {
+        log('ERR', err.message);
+      }
+    });
+  });
+})
+.listen(8080);
+```
+
+When having multiple instance of `AsyncLocal`, they are independant from each
+others. It is safe to instanciate this class multiple times.
+
+### Choosing between asynchronous and synchronous methods
+
+AsyncLocal offer three pair of methods to enter and exit a context:
+* `run/exit`
+* `runAndReturn/exitAndReturn`
+
+#### When to choose `run/exit`
+These methods are asynchronous. They are called with a callback function that
+runs within a new asynchronous call. This is the most explicit behavior as
+everything that is executed within the callback of `run` (including further
+asynchronous operations) will have access to the store. The `exit` method has
+a similar behavior to stop context propagation.
+
+If an instance of AsyncLocal is used for error management (for instance with
+`process.setUncaughtExceptionCaptureCallback`). Only the exceptions thrown
+in the scope of the callback function will be associated with the context.
+
+These methods are the safest to call as they provide strong scoping.
+
+#### When to choose `runAndReturn/exitAndReturn`
+These methods are synchronous and scoped. The callback function will be executed
+synchronously and it's return value will be returned by `runAndReturn`
+and `exitAndReturn`. The store will only be accessible from within the callback
+function and the asynchronous operations created within this scope.
+If the callback throws an error, `runAndReturn` and `exitAndReturn` will throw
+it too.
+
+These methods provide good scoping while being synchronous.
+

