From reading the documentation, it's not entirely clear to me how to use run & exit API in code base using purely Promises, `async` functions and `await` keyword.

Consider a [Koa](https://www.npmjs.com/package/koa) middleware setting up a per-request async storage:

```js
app.use(async (ctx, next) => {
  // create a new scope
  await next();
  // exit the scope
});
```

My first try would be something along the following lines. It looks rather hacky to me, will it even work as intended?

```js
const { AsyncLocal } = require('async_hooks');
const { promisify } = require('util');

const asyncLocal = new AsyncLocal();
asyncLocal.runAsync = promisify(asyncLocal.run);
asyncLocal.exitAsync = promisify(asyncLocal.exit);

const Koa = require('koa');
const app = new Koa();

app.use(async setupClsScope(ctx, next) => {
  await asyncLocal.runAsync();
  await next();
  await asyncLocal.exitAsync();
});
```

Also: what is the interaction of this new feature (async storage) with zero-cost async stack traces provided by V8 for async/await based code? (See https://v8.dev/blog/fast-async#improved-developer-experience). In my example code shown above, when an error is thrown from `exit`, the stack trace should include `setupClsScope` frame. How is this going to work with the callback-based implementation?

